<p>Portion 14:</p>
<p>I want to be clear that although limitations are required for 
existence, it doesn’t matter whether or not there’s human knowledge of 
these limitations. The limits I'm talking about are outlined and stored 
within the fabric of reality. To exist, morality would have to be like 
gravity. Gravity’s existence is not dependent upon humans being aware of
 how gravity works. The laws of physics have existed and held planets in
 the sky long before humans understood their inner workings. Morality 
too cannot exist as a mere product of human imagination because if it 
did, there would be no reason to follow it. This feels a bit weird to 
say since morality governs human behavior. A law that governs human 
behavior can’t exist if there are no humans to govern. I just want to be
 clear though that the law can still exist even if humans don’t know 
about it. Humans have been held subject to the law of gravity since our 
species began and, for most our history, we could not define the laws to
 which we were held.</p>
<p>To improve, every single human must hold himself to a standard 
outside himself. Otherwise, he is the only standard there can ever be. 
If a group of individuals tries to use each other for their standards of
 behavior, none of them can be any better than the individual man. The 
group is made of individual men. The group could not rise to a higher 
standard as a whole any better than they could rise to a higher standard
 individually.<br>
I heard a story recently that illustrates this concept. [Earl 
Nightingale delete once citation added]. There was a businessman who 
would stop in front of the jeweler store every morning and adjust his 
watch to the big clock in the window. The shopkeeper saw this for a 
number of years and didn’t think anything of it. Just went about his 
business. Until one day he got curious and asked the business man,<br>
“You know businessman, you’ve been adjusting your watch to my big clock all these years and I never thought to ask why!”<br>
“I’m the foreman at the factory next door you see,” the man said “and I 
have to blow the quitting whistle at 5pm every day. I want to make sure I
 get the time right, so I know how much to pay the men.”<br>
The shopkeeper rubbed his chin and was silent for a moment until he 
finally said, “you know, that’s funny, because I’ve been adjusting my 
big clock to your quitting whistle all these years.”<br>
The two men had been adjusting their clocks based on each other. It’s 
possible that they were only off by a small margin. Then again, they 
could’ve been off by months! Since they were each other’s standard, and 
neither of them was consistent, there’s no way to tell how many hours of
 work had actually been done at the factory. The only way to measure the
 factory hours correctly, would be to correct the clocks by consulting 
some consistent source rather than the two changing standards. If there 
wasn’t an outside source to consult about what time the clocks should 
run on, then there would never be any way to be certain about how much 
work had been done. Why even have a clock in the first place at that 
point? If the sun couldn’t measure time, the spinning of the earth 
couldn’t measure time, if all measurements outside of those two clocks 
were stripped away, what use would there be for the concept of time? It 
would be meaningless randomized measurement.<br>
Each individual’s moral standard is like these two clocks. Our moral 
standards constantly change because individuals themselves constantly 
change. If we orient ourselves by something that changes, we will never 
know how close or far off we are from the real thing. Unless we’re 
saying there is no real thing, in which case, why are we bothering with 
it anyway? When it comes to moral law, there isn’t a single person alive
 who’s good enough to be a consistent moral standard. Since groups of 
humans are made of individual humans, there’s also no group of humans 
alive good enough to be a consistent moral standard. If morality is 
derived from mere human imagination, then the concept of morality is 
just as useless as time derived from two clocks following each other 
with no outside reference. For morality to exist, there must be some 
definition outside ourselves that we can work to understand. This brings
 us back to choosing between our two main options. Does morality exist 
or not?</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">5:32 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230691607509"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I
