that faith is a good interim solution when we are unable to do the 
calculations ourselves, or when we don’t have the resources to know an 
answer to its fullest. We can’t do the calculations to measure 
everything ourselves. Another person may know a thing for certain, 
having done the calculations, but we often find ourselves in need of 
simply placing faith in their knowledge of the subject. Faith is not 
some hokey-pokey word. When we don’t have the time or resources to learn
 an issue, we must put faith in those who have our best interests at 
heart.<br>
The importance of seeking after our own knowledge is clear. As we come 
to understand the foundations of knowledge, in any subject, we’ll be 
less buffeted by those who do not have our best interests at heart. 
We’ll be less buffeted by lies. It seems to me, that as we seek after 
truth, other truth seekers also attend a similar process so that we can 
know when someone has our best interests at heart, by the way they fight
 to understand the truth for themselves.</p>
<p>This being said, it is possible that someone could become a hermit 
