<p>Portion 18</p>
<p>This being said, it is possible that someone could become a hermit 
and live entirely on their own. To only do those things which he 
understands fully how to do by himself. Even then he must live on faith.
 He does not know for sure that the sun will rise every day. He does not
 know without a shadow of a doubt that the river will continue running, 
or that every time he steps out of his cave he will be safe. I’m sure 
most people would agree that cavemen were the most ignorant group of our
 species. Not knowing how to produce machines, or to farm, or to write. 
No matter what we do, all of us are ignorant in some ways.</p>
<p>Particularly when it comes to the question: “Does a moral law exist or not?”</p>
<p>There are only two options. Either we choose to believe that morality
 exists, or we choose to believe it doesn’t. There’s no way to escape 
this choice. There is no magical third option from which we can 
logically base our belief. There are only two logical options. Since 
morality can’t be proven, and inaction is impossible, the question must 
be a choice to believe one way or the other. Regardless which option you
 choose, this choice is something that you will not be able to prove.</p>
<p>This book is not meant to trap you. We’re already trapped. I hope to 
shed light on the nature of our predicament so we can understand how to 
make the most of our situation. I don’t know if death is an escape from 
existence. None of us do. It all boils down to that singular question, 
“is there a law of morality or not?”. It has been my experience that 
taking hold of the choice and choosing deliberately rather than being 
thrown around trying to escape the inescapable, or trying to prove the 
unprovable, is what provides freedom and peace for the soul.</p>
<p>Since one belief or the other must be true, regardless of our wishes,
 it is in our best interest to be aware of this choice and to act upon 
it consciously. To understand our choices, let’s make a pros and cons 
chart! Growing up, any time I needed to make a decision, my Mom would 
always harp on the value of a pros and cons chart. It hasn’t failed me 
yet.</p>
